  "suggestion": "[dynamical-systems+computational-neuroscience+clinical-psychology] IMPLEMENT NOW — Attractor Landscape Dynamics. Replace the single free-energy computation with a small set of behavioral attractors per domain. Model each person as a dynamical system with 3-5 stable states (attractors) and a current position. The stimulus applies a force vector; the response is the attractor the system falls into — not whichever need has highest free energy, but which basin of attraction captures the trajectory. Key insight: trauma = deep narrow attractors; healthy flexibility = shallow wide attractors; psychopathology = hyper-stable attractors that resist perturbation. Implementation: for each domain, define attractor states (e.g. approach/avoid/freeze for threat stimuli); compute 'basin depth' from arousal × history length; the deepest attractor near current trajectory wins. This directly explains habit formation, therapy-as-basin-reshaping, and why willpower alone fails against strong attractors. — Math: dX/dt = -∇V(X) + F_stimulus; V(X) = Σ_i depth_i · (|X - attractor_i|²); response = argmin_i |X_final - attractor_i|; [narrative-psychology+cognitive-linguistics+identity-theory+McAdams-life-story] IMPLEMENT NOW — Narrative Coherence Scoring as Root Cause Engine. The brain's core job is to maintain a coherent self-narrative. Every response is chosen to maximize narrative coherence with the person's existing beliefs and history. Root cause = the belief/narrative that is threatened or confirmed. Implementation: extract 2-3 narrative themes from person.beliefs and person.history; score each possible response by how well it preserves narrative coherence (does it explain the stimulus in terms the person already understands?); the highest-coherence response wins. This unifies cognitive dissonance, rationalization, confirmation bias, identity-protective cognition, and self-serving attribution under one mechanism — all are narrative-preservation strategies. Concrete: if beliefs contain 'I am competent' and stimulus is failure, rootCause = 'threat to competence narrative', process = 'externalize blame to preserve narrative', behavior = 'blame external factors'. — Math: coherence(response | beliefs, history) = Σ_b sim(response.rootCause, b) / |beliefs|; choose response* = argmax coherence; [affective-neuroscience+temporal-difference-learning+computational-psychiatry+Northoff-2016] REFINEMENT — Prediction Horizon Collapse as Unified Psychopathology Mechanism. The current psychopathology domain uses hyper-vigilance (safety precision 10×) which is correct for anxiety/PTSD but wrong for depression and other disorders. Unify psychopathology via prediction horizon: a healthy person integrates predictions across multiple timescales (seconds → years). Depression = collapsed horizon (only immediate past matters, future is inaccessible — explains anhedonia and hopelessness). Anxiety = horizon is intact but threat precision is amplified at ALL timescales. Mania = horizon overextended with inflated reward priors. OCD = ultra-short horizon (only this moment's certainty counts). Implementation: add person.predictionHorizon (0.0-1.0) derived from arousal + history valence; when horizon < 0.3, collapse future-oriented needs (achievement, autonomy) to near-zero; when horizon > 0.9, amplify reward priors 2×. This produces qualitatively distinct pathology profiles from one continuous parameter. — Math: horizon h = clip(1 - arousal × 0.5 - historyNegativity × 0.5, 0, 1); need_weight(need, h) = base_weight × (1 - futurity(need) × (1 - h)); futurity ∈ {achievement:0.9, autonomy:0.7, belonging:0.4, safety:0.1}",
